We performed SEM to obtain a preliminary understanding of the morphology of X at self-assembled states in different solvents (Fig. 4
                         and S6). The molecules of X could be self-assembled into microfiber through intermolecular hydrogen bonds and further assembled by feeble π-π stacking into ribbon fibers as the secondary structure of the gel. Finally, these velvet fibers were wound into 3D networks to lock the solvent molecules to constitute a gel. Interestingly, the gels formed after adding CH2Cl2, CHCl3, THF and DMSO were composed of microfibers with higher density, smaller structure and more uniform dispersion. Furthermore, the molecular packing arrangement of the xerogels were characterized by XRD (Fig. 5
                        ). From CH3OH to DMSO-CH3OH, the diffraction peaks in the high angle region became more sharper and visible, which was associate to the enhancement of the interaction between gelators. Equally, similar situations occurred when adding the high solubility solvents to X in ethanol (Fig. S7).
